  "text": "Determining FcγR usage. FcγR usage was determined after altering Fc binding in 3 ways. First, Fc binding was changed using previously described [CITATION_1] . In brief, the Fc domain of VRC01 Ab was point mutated to alter the Ab's affinity for different FcγRs. VRC01 WT maintains all WT amino acids and the strongest binding to FcγR1. The FcγR2A Ab contains a point mutation at position 236 from a glycine to an alanine, which confers strongest binding to the 2A receptor. The FcγR2B Ab contains 2 point mutations, 1 at position 239, a serine to an aspartic acid, and 1 at position 332, an isoleucine to a glutamic acid, both of which confer strongest binding to the 2B receptor. The FcγR3A Ab contains 3 point mutations; the first 2 are present in the FcγR2B Ab, S239D, and I332E, the third mutation is at position 330, an alanine to leucine, all 3 of which confer strongest binding to the FcγR3A receptor. Finally, the no-binding Ab has a point mutation at the N-linked glycosylation site, position 237, an asparagine to glutamine, which prevents binding to all FcγRs. These mutations have no effect on the affinity or avidity of the Fab domain of the VRC01 Ab. The second method used was Ab deglycosylation. Abs were digested using the nondenaturing protocol and the PNGase-F Remove-iT enzyme (New England BioLabs). In brief, 20 μg of 4E10 was added to GlycoBuffer2 and H 2 O to make a 1× 20 μl reaction; the mixture was incubated at 37°C overnight. The PNGase-F enzyme was then removed using Chitin Magnetic beads (New England BioLabs) per the manufacturer's recommendations. The third method utilized a polyclonal Ab against FcγR2 to sterically block interactions as previously described [CITATION_2] . In brief, after isolation, pDCs were cultured with 10 μg/ml of goat anti-human FcγR2 pAb (R&D Systems) and incubated at 37°C for 1 hour. Virus with and without HIV Ab was then added to the pDCs and IFN-α production measured after 15 hours. Cells were stained with a PE mouse anti-human CD32 (BD Biosciences) to confirm that FcR2 was blocked during the course of the experiment.",
